metadata.name: KINJO! #32
metadata.description:
A celebration of my 1 year in the Tezos art space, KINJO is an experiment in pure abstraction and randomness. With a simple grid at its core, this piece attempts to play with lively colors, completely unique variations, and host the nice surprises that randomness can bring.

My intention when starting to work in the Tezos space was to play with the surrender of control in art, that idea had always fascinated me. In the beginning it was working with GAN, digitally painting a piece or processing my own photography, and sending it through my own frankensteined colab notebook. I was creating something and then trusting a process to rip it apart and create something new. I moved on to the Ganerations project, which was essentially gen art in layered pngs and processed through my GAN notebook. I found generative art and fxHash shortly after and have been incredibly thankful for the community here, as well as inspired every day by the new approaches I see from both new and established artists on the platform. I'm learning every day.

Gen art is the perfect place for me to express myself and explore the themes of control and trust with my work, and I thank you all for following along and supporting my work :)

metadata.name: Cold materials #267
Cold materials #236
Faux #202
metadata.description:
This project is borne out of my longstanding fascination with brushwork, and the intricate textures that can be created with a brush, some paint and a canvas. Brush strokes are simulated using many overlapping lines and given texture and depth using a custom shader. Another important aspect of this work, is the composite forms that are created by the brush strokes, which are my attempt to emulate the emphatic energy of many abstract painters that have come before me. Color palettes are named after common paint colors, based on the background color used for the palette.

Those who collect during the first tier of the Dutch Auction can claim a signed print. They will be printed on A3 Hahnemuhle Photo Rag, and shipped to the collector free of charge. More details on how to claim a print and specify the necessary shipping information will be provided via the artists twitter (@landlinesart1).

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: fx(ornament) 2022 #1088
metadata.description:
Tis the season to celebrate and what better way than with a collectible series of 2022 generative ornaments. Perfect for yourself or as gifts for people you love. 

Designed to be printed or plotted and then cut out and hung on your tree or any other place that needs a little festive cheer. 

I’ll be picking a few of my favorite outputs and sending the token owners special limited edition signed laser cut versions of their ornaments. 

———————

LIVE MODE FEATURES
- L prepares it for plotting or cutting
- S exports a layered SVG
- P exports a PNG
- 1-9 plays with color combos

———————

For years my family has collected Wallace Silver Candy Cane ornaments. Each Christmas the kids open up that years design and add it to the tree. With my daughters mostly grown, we now have quite the collection of dozens of ornaments from all the years. Each one full with memories and emotions. 

This series is inspired by that tradition, starting with 2022, and continuing with a new release each year. I hope you enjoy this series and it brings much delight and joy to you, your family, and friends this holiday season.

metadata.name: Cold materials #213
Attractor #221
metadata.description:
People are often drawn together over shared interest, and through their connections to those interests they find connections with others. Attractor is a visualization of community, a central interest bringing people together, pushing past their walls, bad habits, and traumas. The image is meant to be deceiving in its focus on the attractor, where the true focus is on the overlaps and complex defenses we build around ourselves. Those defenses can make us and those connections into more beautiful, ornate structures, or keep us distant from those around us. Sometimes focusing on a shared attractor is the only way we can let down our guard.

Press ’s’ to save a .png
Press ’t’ to toggle the grain for printing or personal preference
Press ‘p’ to save a higher quality .png
Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Inland Emotions #135
metadata.description:
Inland Emotions

Over the centuries, ancient philosophers and modern psychologists have come to the same basic conclusion. The fact is that, according to a few millennia of research, there are a limited number of distinct human emotions, predefined by the human psyche. Sometimes it may seem like we are experiencing a "new" one, but on closer inspection, we see that it is the known emotions that are superimposed. Emotions are what they are, and they exist in the same way in each of us, whether we recognize them for what they are or not. But as our history blends into a new emerging state of the world, a whole new range of emotional responses are triggered within us. An infinite maelstrom of variations generated from a simple combination of a few emotions.


Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

metadata.name: Constellation Of Happiness #305
metadata.description:
Constellation Of Happiness is a collaborative art project between NFT artists Kato Trofimova and Andrew Erickson.

Feeling happy is tough this year but it'll be much easier when you get your own constellation of happiness! Using expressionistic code art, Constellation Of Happiness channels the purest festive emotions a person can experience, for example, when tasting champagne bubbles or seeing and touching confetti. All these are turned into beautiful constellations of happiness using the aesthetics of star maps and carefully brought to your NFT collection.

2022

Kato Trofimova (Latvia) is an illustrator, visual artist, and creative director known for her love of minimalistic shapes and bright palettes. In her art, Kato questions boundaries between styles and stays optimistic no matter what.

Andrew Erickson (Switzerland) is a generative artist experimenting with various abstract styles. Be it delicate monochromatic line art or colorful gradient minimalism, Andrew is very good at coding any kind of digital beauty.

Hit 'p' in live mode to save a 9922 × 14032px PNG (for printing up to A0)
Hit 's' in live mode to save a plottable SVG

10% of proceeds go to support Processing.org

License: CC BY-NC-SA-4.0

metadata.name: The Past Ahead #54
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

metadata.name: GRAPHEME #86
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke. 
www.tribute-hwf.com

“One criterion for art involves the process used by the artist for shaping the work. In the special case of mathematically supported fine art, the artmaking process occurs in a mathematically defined operation that allows the generation and transformation of images, methods used for picture processing.” - Herbert W. Franke

I first came across Franke’s ‘Ornamental Alphabets’ in his book 𝘊𝘰𝘮𝘱𝘶𝘵𝘦𝘳 𝘎𝘳𝘢𝘱𝘩𝘪𝘤𝘴 - 𝘊𝘰𝘮𝘱𝘶𝘵𝘦𝘳 𝘈𝘳𝘵, and was intrigued with the idea of using a simple letterform to explore different generative image processing techniques. 

I’ve used letters and writing in my work for a long time, both with letterpress printing and in my asemic poetry programs. With asemic writing, I generate unrecognizable letters to reference text, and here I use recognizable letterforms removed from their typical function as language signifiers. 

My goal with this project was to build as much texture and layering as possible by warping and collaging the letters together in various ways. The font I’m using is a design I made years ago to supplement my wood type collection for printing. I really enjoyed being able to bring that part of my past work into my generative art practice. 

Each image is composed of the letters found in the hash for that piece, divided into either vowels or consonants. The program builds on a technique I’ve used before, where I generate an image to an off-screen canvas and then dive through the pixels to pull out the color and form I want to surface in the final image.

25% of the primary sales will be donated on-chain to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke. These funds will be used by ZKM Karlsruhe to digitize Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. Any additional funds raised will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.

- Press “R” to increase the pixel density and reload the image (this can be render intensive and will create a really large file suitable for printing)
- Press “S” to save a copy

Made with p5js
Artist: Sarah Ridgley
October, 2022

metadata.name: pantonX.1 #13
metadata.description:
pantonX.1

I am a visual artist and have worked in the field of coding since the early years of processing.
Always loved geometric and minimalist art, bauhaus, De Stijl, Piet Mondrian, Ellsworth Kelly, Imi Knoebel -- just to name a few -- and last but not least Verner Panton, have had a big influence on my artistic work.

pantonX.1 is my first fxhash release. it's coded in p5js.
I set up a wider random range for the color arrays and the division structure, so that a 100x drop would have enough variation for not getting boring. 

The "s" key is for saving. Use your pc window scaling for exporting higher resolutions.

metadata.name: The Living Book #1 #28
metadata.description:
I have been exploring the medium of print for years. Mixing etching, silk-screening, offset, photocopy, risography, drawing and painting to design and craft experimental art books.From the day digital, which had always fascinated me, took over my publishing practice, I always liked to create bridges between these two worlds.

The Living Books is part of this series of hybrid and experimental works where paper and digital resonate.

This issue #1 is made of 64 pages that will be minted by collectors. A book will eventually be printed and the pages will follow the mint order. Each page exists in a cover version (c) and a xerox version (x).

Controls :

• Click to dive into each frame.
• Press C to toggle cover mode.
• Press X to toggle xerox mode.
• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

The Living Book #1 by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity
